1. Read in the data

if (!file.exists("met_all.gz"))
  download.file(
    url = "https://raw.githubusercontent.com/USCbiostats/data-science-data/master/02_met/met_all.gz",
    destfile = "met_all.gz",
    method   = "libcurl",
    timeout  = 60
    )
met <- data.table::fread("met_all.gz")

2. Prepare the data

met <- met[temp >= -17][elev == 9999.0, elev := NA]
summary(met$temp)

summary(met$wind.sp)
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max.    NA's 
##    0.00    0.00    2.10    2.46    3.60   36.00   31743
#Generate a date variable using the functions as.Date() (hint: You will need the following to create a date paste(year, month, day, sep = "-")).
library(lubridate)
met= met[ , ymd := as.Date(paste(year, month, day, sep = "-"))]
met[, table(week(ymd))]
## 
##     31     32     33     34     35 
## 297260 521605 527924 523847 446576
met= met[week(ymd)==31]
#Compute the mean by station of the variables temp, rh, wind.sp, vis.dist, dew.point, lat, lon, and elev.
met[, .(
  temp= max(temp, na.rm=T),
  rh= max(rh, na.rm=T),
  wind.sp= max(wind.sp, na.rm=T),
  vis.dist= max(vis.dist, na.rm=T), 
  dew.point= max(dew.point, na.rm=T), 
  lat= max(lat, na.rm=T), 
  lon= max(lon, na.rm=T), 
  elev= max(elev, na.rm=T)
)]
##    temp  rh wind.sp vis.dist dew.point    lat     lon elev
## 1:   47 100    20.6   144841        29 48.941 -68.313 4113
met_avg= met[, .(
  temp= mean(temp, na.rm=T),
  rh= mean(rh, na.rm=T),
  wind.sp= mean(wind.sp, na.rm=T),
  vis.dist= mean(vis.dist, na.rm=T), 
  dew.point= mean(dew.point, na.rm=T), 
  lat= mean(lat, na.rm=T), 
  lon= mean(lon, na.rm=T), 
  elev= mean(elev, na.rm=T)
), by= 'USAFID']
#create a region variable
library(dtplyr)
library(data.table)
met_avg= met_avg[ , region := fifelse(lon>= -98 & lat> 39.71, "NE",
                 fifelse(lon< -98 & lat> 39.71, "NW",
                 fifelse(lon< -98 & lat<= 39.71, "SW","SE")))
     ]
table(met_avg$region)
## 
##  NE  NW  SE  SW 
## 484 146 649 297
#create a categorical variable for elevation
met_avg[, elev_cat := fifelse(elev >252, "high", "low")]

3. Use geom_violin to examine the wind speed and dew point temperature by region

library(ggplot2)
met_avg[!is.na(region)] %>% 
  ggplot() + 
  geom_violin(mapping = aes(x = 1, y = dew.point, color=region, fill= region)) + 
  facet_wrap(~ region, nrow = 1)
## Warning: Removed 1 rows containing non-finite values (stat_ydensity).

Thus, the highest dew point temp is in se.

met_avg[!is.na(region) & !is.na(wind.sp)] %>% 
  ggplot() + 
  geom_violin(mapping = aes(x = 1, y = wind.sp, color=region, fill= region)) + 
  facet_wrap(~ region, nrow = 2)

Thus, ne has the highest wind speed

##4. Use geom_jitter with stat_smooth to examine the association between dew point temperature and wind speed by region

8.Use a ggplot extension

rhmap <- leaflet(met_avg) %>% 
  # The looks of the Map
  addProviderTiles('CartoDB.Positron') %>% 
  # Some circles
  addCircles(
    lat = ~lat, lng=~lon,
                                                  # HERE IS OUR PAL!
    label = ~paste0(rh), color = ~ rh.pal(rh),
    opacity = 1, fillOpacity = 1, radius = 500
    ) %>%
  # And a pretty legend
  addLegend('bottomleft', pal=rh.pal, values=met_avg$rh,
          title='Releative Hunid.', opacity=1)
rhmap
